ğŸŒ Introduction to AWS

AWS (Amazon Web Services) is a cloud computing platform provided by Amazon.
It offers on-demand services such as computing power, storage, databases, networking, machine learning, and more â€” all delivered over the internet (the â€œcloudâ€).

âš™ï¸ Key Idea

Instead of buying and maintaining physical servers or data centers, organizations can use AWS to:

Run applications

Store data

Host websites

Analyze information

Deploy software globally

This helps save cost, time, and resources.

â˜ï¸ Main Categories of AWS Services

Compute â€“ Services that provide processing power.
Example: Amazon EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)

Storage â€“ For saving and retrieving data.
Example: Amazon S3 (Simple Storage Service)

Database â€“ Managed databases for structured and unstructured data.
Example: Amazon RDS (Relational Database Service)

Networking â€“ Services for secure and fast network connections.
Example: Amazon VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)

Security & Identity â€“ To control access and protect resources.
Example: IAM (Identity and Access Management)

Machine Learning, Analytics, and DevOps tools â€“ For smart automation and monitoring.

ğŸ’¡ Benefits of AWS

